fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
For example, consider the following terms:
\begin {array}{c} \lambda x. \lambda y. \lambda z. x \\ \lambda x. \lambda y. \lambda z. y \\ \lambda x. \lambda y. \lambda z. z \end {array}
In the first term, the variable x is bound by the first lambda which is two binding sites away. As a result, it is represented by the index 2. Similarly, in the second term, the variable y is bound by the second lambda, so it is represented by the index 1. Lastly, the variable z is bound by the third lambda, so it is represented by the index 0. This gives us the following indexed representations of these closed terms:
\begin {align*} \lambda \overset {\red {2}}{\vphantom {y}x}. \lambda \overset {\gray {1}}{y}. \lambda \overset {\gray {0}}{\vphantom {y}z}. \underset {\red {2}}{x} &\equiv \lambda \lambda \lambda \red {2} \\ \lambda \overset {\gray {2}}{x}. \lambda \overset {\red {1}}{y}. \lambda \overset {\gray {0}}{\vphantom {y}z}. \underset {\red {1}}{y} &\equiv \lambda \lambda \lambda \red {1} \\ \lambda \overset {\gray {2}}{x}. \lambda \overset {\gray {1}}{y}. \lambda \overset {\red {0}}{\vphantom {y}z}. \underset {\red {0}}{z} &\equiv \lambda \lambda \lambda \red {0} \end {align*}

Both de Bruijn indices and de Bruijn levels eliminate the need for \alpha -conversion. However, each has different affordances that make one better suited for certain operations over the other. For instance, indices are better suited for substitution of closed terms than levels, e.g.,
\begin {aligned} & \lambda \overset {\red {2}}{\vphantom {y}x}. \lambda \overset {\gray {1}}{y}. \lambda \overset {\gray {0}}{\vphantom {y}z}. \underset {\red {2}}{x}~ \lambda \overset {\red {0}}{\vphantom {y}x}. \underset {\red {0}}{x} &\equiv & \lambda \lambda \lambda \red {2}~\lambda \red {0} \\ \rightarrow _\beta ~ & \lambda y. \lambda z. \lambda \overset {\red {0}}{\vphantom {y}x}. \underset {\red {0}}{x} &\equiv & \lambda \lambda \lambda \red {0} \end {aligned}
versus
\begin {aligned} & \lambda \overset {\red {0}}{\vphantom {y}x}. \lambda \overset {\gray {1}}{y}. \lambda \overset {\gray {2}}{\vphantom {y}z}. \underset {\red {0}}{x}~ \lambda \overset {\red {0}}{\vphantom {y}x}. \underset {\red {0}}{x} &\equiv & \lambda \lambda \lambda \red {0}~\lambda \red {0} \\ \rightarrow _\beta ~ & \lambda \overset {\gray {1}}{y}. \lambda \overset {\gray {2}}{\vphantom {y}z}. \lambda \overset {\red {0}}{\vphantom {y}x}. \underset {\red {0}}{x} &\equiv & \lambda \lambda \lambda \red {0} \left .\right \rbrace \hbox {\footnotesize \text {bad levels}}\\ \rightarrow ~ & \lambda \overset {\gray {0}}{y}. \lambda \overset {\gray {1}}{\vphantom {y}z}. \lambda \overset {\red {2}}{\vphantom {y}x}. \underset {\red {2}}{x} &\equiv & \lambda \lambda \lambda \red {2} \end {aligned}
Levels require shifting here, because, first, the application eliminates the outermost binder and, therefore, alters the root, and second, the new innermost subterm must be adjusted to align with the root. In contrast, indices are relative to the binding site which means that their alignment is preserved.

For example, consider the following terms:
\begin {array}{c} \lambda x. \lambda y. \lambda z. x \\ \lambda x. \lambda y. \lambda z. y \\ \lambda x. \lambda y. \lambda z. z \end {array}
In the first term, the variable x is bound by the first lambda which is two binding sites away. As a result, it is represented by the index 2. Similarly, in the second term, the variable y is bound by the second lambda, so it is represented by the index 1. Lastly, the variable z is bound by the third lambda, so it is represented by the index 0. This gives us the following indexed representations of these closed terms:
\begin {align*} \lambda \overset {\red {2}}{\vphantom {y}x}. \lambda \overset {\gray {1}}{y}. \lambda \overset {\gray {0}}{\vphantom {y}z}. \underset {\red {2}}{x} &\equiv \lambda \lambda \lambda \red {2} \\ \lambda \overset {\gray {2}}{x}. \lambda \overset {\red {1}}{y}. \lambda \overset {\gray {0}}{\vphantom {y}z}. \underset {\red {1}}{y} &\equiv \lambda \lambda \lambda \red {1} \\ \lambda \overset {\gray {2}}{x}. \lambda \overset {\gray {1}}{y}. \lambda \overset {\red {0}}{\vphantom {y}z}. \underset {\red {0}}{z} &\equiv \lambda \lambda \lambda \red {0} \end {align*}

For example, consider the following terms:
\begin {array}{c} \lambda x. \lambda y. \lambda z. x \\ \lambda x. \lambda y. \lambda z. y \\ \lambda x. \lambda y. \lambda z. z \end {array}
In the first term, the variable x is bound by the first lambda which is two binding sites away. As a result, it is represented by the index 2. Similarly, in the second term, the variable y is bound by the second lambda, so it is represented by the index 1. Lastly, the variable z is bound by the third lambda, so it is represented by the index 0. This gives us the following indexed representations of these closed terms:
\begin {align*} \lambda \overset {\red {2}}{\vphantom {y}x}. \lambda \overset {\gray {1}}{y}. \lambda \overset {\gray {0}}{\vphantom {y}z}. \underset {\red {2}}{x} &\equiv \lambda \lambda \lambda \red {2} \\ \lambda \overset {\gray {2}}{x}. \lambda \overset {\red {1}}{y}. \lambda \overset {\gray {0}}{\vphantom {y}z}. \underset {\red {1}}{y} &\equiv \lambda \lambda \lambda \red {1} \\ \lambda \overset {\gray {2}}{x}. \lambda \overset {\gray {1}}{y}. \lambda \overset {\red {0}}{\vphantom {y}z}. \underset {\red {0}}{z} &\equiv \lambda \lambda \lambda \red {0} \end {align*}
